th Street (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show}}\n|June 22, 1915\n|Southern terminal for trains<br>[[MetroCard]] transfer to [[IND Culver Line]] ({{NYCS Culver IND south|time=show}}) at [[Avenue X (IND Culver Line)|Avenue X]]\n|-\n!colspan=7 style=\"background-color: silver;\"|Center express tracks end\n|-\n!colspan=7 style=\"background-color: silver;\"|connecting tracks to [[Coney Island Complex|Coney Island Yard]]\n|-\n|[[Coney Island]]\n||{{Access icon}}\n|nowrap|[[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]]\n|all\n|\n|December 13, 1918\n|[[BMT Brighton Line]] ({{NYCS Brighton south|time=show}})<br />[[IND Culver Line]] ({{NYCS Culver IND south|time=show}})<br />[[BMT West End Line]] ({{NYCS West End far south|time=show}})<br />Service does not stop here due to flood protection work until April 27, 2020.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Transportation to Coney Island]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*Rapid Transit's Coney Island Route, ''[[The New York Times]]'' November 30, 1897 page 4\n*Brooklyn's Subway Will Open Today, ''The New York Times'' June 19, 1915 page 18\n*New Subway Opens; Mayor Not Present, ''The New York Times'' June 20, 1915 page 6\n*To Open New Subway Link, ''The New York Times'' January 14, 1916 page 16\n*Open First Section of Broadway Line, ''The New York Times'' September 5, 1917 page 8\n*New Subway Extension, ''The New York Times'' January 6, 1918 page 37\n\n==External links==\n{{attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons category|BMT Sea Beach Line}}\n*[http://www.nycsubway.org/bmt/seabeach/ nycsubway.org - BMT Sea Beach Line]\n*[http://www.nycsubway.org/bmt/history01.html nycsubway.org - Early Rapid Transit in Brooklyn, 1878 to 1913]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050404084915/http://www.rapidtransit.net/net/faq/nyc/seabeach.html rapidtransit.net - BMT Sea Beach Express Tracks]\n\n{{NYCS lines navbox}}\n{{NYCS navbox}}\n{{BMT companies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sea Beach}}\n[[Category:Brooklyn-Manhattan Transit Corporation]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway lines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|New York City Subway line}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name = BMT Sea Beach Line\n| image = {{rint|nycs|N|size=50px}}\n| image_width = 75px\n| caption = The [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] serves the entire Sea Beach Line at all times.<br>Limited rush-hour service is also provided by the [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]].\n| type = [[Rapid transit]]\n| system = [[New York City Subway]]\n| start = [[Eighth Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Eighth Avenue]]\n| end = [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]]\n| stations = 10\n| open = 1915\u20131918\n| owner = [[New York City|City of New York]]\n| operator = [[New York City Transit Authority]]\n| character = Open-Cut<br />Elevated (<small>at Stillwell Avenue</small>)\n| linelength = \n| tracks = 2-4\n| gauge = {{RailGauge|ussg}}\n|electrification = [[Direct current traction|600V DC third rail]]\n|map = {{BMT Sea Beach Line|inline=1}}\n| map_state = collapsed\n}}\n\nThe '''BMT Sea Beach Line''' is a [[rapid transit]] line of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation|BMT]] division of the [[New York City Subway]], connecting the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] at [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]] via a four-track wide open cut to [[Coney Island]] in [[Brooklyn]]. It has at times hosted the fastest express service between [[Manhattan]] and Coney Island, since there are no express stations along the entire stretch, but now carries only local trains on the [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] service, which serves the entire line at all times. The line north of [[86th Street (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street]] is also served by a few [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains during rush hours in the peak direction.\n\n==Extent and service==\nThe following services use part or all of the BMT Sea Beach Line:<ref>{{NYCS const|serviceguide}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!&nbsp;\n!Time period\n!Section of line\n|-\n|{{rint|newyork|N}}\n|all times\n|full line\n|-\n|{{rint|newyork|W}}\n|three rush hour trains<br/>in the peak direction\n|north of [[86th Street (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street]]\n|}\n[[File:N approaching 6 Av in BR trench jeh.JPG|left|thumb|225px|Open cut, looking west from 6th Avenue overpass, with the LIRR [[Bay Ridge Branch]] on the left and the BMT Sea Beach Line on the right.]]\n[[File:16th Av powerhouse Sea Beach jeh.JPG|left|thumb|225px|16th Avenue powerhouse]]\n\n===Route description===\n\nThe modern line begins as a split from the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] at a [[flying junction]] immediately south of [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. Between the station and the split, [[Crossover (rail)|crossover switches]] are provided between the local and express tracks of the Fourth Avenue Line, and then the express tracks curve east under the northbound local track to become the beginning of the Sea Beach Line. After emerging from the tunnel under Fourth Avenue, the two separate Sea Beach tracks rise on either side of a ramp which formerly connected to the original line to the Brooklyn shore at 65th Street in [[Bay Ridge, Brooklyn|Bay Ridge]].<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref>\n\nAfter passing the former junction with the line to the shore, the Sea Beach widens to the width of four tracks. All stations have two side platforms with no platform access to the express tracks anywhere on the Sea Beach right-of-way.<ref name=\"tracks\" />\n\nBefore and after [[Kings Highway (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Kings Highway]], there are crossover switches to the southbound express track from the northbound express track. On both sides of Kings Highway, crossovers exist to allow express trains to switch to the local tracks before the station or local trains to switch to express after the station. The express tracks end south of [[86th Street (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street]] as the line becomes double-tracked, and cut diagonally adjacent to the [[Coney Island Complex|Coney Island Yards]]. After several [[railroad yard|yard]] connections, the line ends at the [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]] terminal.<ref name=\"tracks\" />\n\n===Express tracks===\n\nThe express tracks were originally intended to host the ''Coney Island Express''. Service was carried on these tracks twice in the line's history &mdash; for summer weekend service to [[Chambers Street (BMT Nassau Street Line)|Chambers Street]] from 1924\u20131952 and again from 1967-1968 to provide a fast rush-hour [[BMT Broadway Line|Broadway Line]] express service for Coney Island riders ([[NX (New York City Subway service)|NX]]). Though these expresses are thought of as being Sea Beach Expresses, they did not serve a single station on the Sea Beach Line.\n\nThe express tracks on the Sea Beach had other uses over the years. Most new equipment, especially experimental cars, was broken in on these tracks. The tracks were used for [[Motorman (locomotive)|motorman]] training and set up with a short stretch of 1950s-era [[automation]] to test the ill-fated system later used on one track of the [[IRT 42nd Street Shuttle]].\n\nHistorically, the two express tracks were an absolute block, that is, there was no signal control between one end of the tracks near Sixth Avenue and [[Kings Highway (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Kings Highway]]. A train was not supposed to enter the block until any train in front of it had departed the block.\n\nThe express tracks' section on this block was allowed to deteriorate severely as did much of the system from the 1970s on. In 1998, it was decided to rehabilitate the express tracks in this area, with full signaling. Only the northbound (E4) track was rehabilitated, however, for two-way traffic from its northern end to Kings Highway if needed. The southbound (E3) track remains unused, being disconnected from the other three tracks and inaccessible from [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]] to Kings Highway.<ref name=\"tracks\" />\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:Bmt triplex no 4.png|thumb|90px|Route designation on BMT Triplex equipment|alt=]]\n\nThe '''New York and Sea Beach Railroad''' was organized on September 25, 1876 as a [[steam-powered]] excursion railroad. It opened from a junction with the [[Brooklyn, Bath and Coney Island Railroad]] (West End Line) and concurrently-opened [[New York, Bay Ridge and Jamaica Railroad]] (Manhattan Beach Line) to Coney Island on July 18, 1877.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Another Line Open|date = 17 July 1877|page=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=The Sea Beach Railroad|date = 19 July 1877|page=2}}</ref> After a delay of two years, it was opened to the Bay Ridge Ferry (to [[South Ferry, Manhattan]]) on July 17, 1879, at which time the Sea Beach Palace opened at the Coney Island end.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Sea Beach|date = 15 July 1879|page=2}}</ref><!--the only station mentioned is \"Gunther's Junction\", earlier called \"Bay Ridge Junction\"--><ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=The First Train|date = 17 July 1879|page=4}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 2015|title=Two Anniversaries\u2013Sea Beach and Steinway Tunnel|url=https://issuu.com/erausa/docs/2015-08-bulletin|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=New York Division, Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=58|issue=8|doi=|pmid=|access-date=August 31, 2016|via=Issu}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Station AvenueU.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Station headhouse at [[Avenue U (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Avenue U]] station.]]\n\nExcept at its two ends, the railroad used the same route as the current Sea Beach Line. At the Bay Ridge end, the railroad ran just north of the [[Long Island Rail Road]]'s Bay Ridge Branch, ending at the Bay Ridge Channel around 64th Street. The current line joins this alignment near Fifth Avenue. The old railroad crossed the Bay Ridge Branch with a pronounced S-curve just east of Seventh Avenue; the crossing is now much straighter with the Bay Ridge Branch in a deeper cut. On the Coney Island end, the original path curved left soon after the curve to the right at the northern edge of the Coney Island Yards, ending at the combined Sea Beach Palace hotel and depot, on the north side of the [[BMT Brighton Line]] at around West 10th Street.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn May 22, 1883, the company was reorganized as the New York and Sea Beach Railway Company and was allowed to operate from New York Harbor to the Sea Beach Palace in Coney Island. The company went bankrupt, and a receiver was appointed on January 15, 1896, before the company was sold at foreclosure by the '''Sea Beach Railway''', which was incorporated on August 29, 1896. The [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT) bought the company's stock on November 5, 1897, along with the short [[elevated railway|elevated]] Sea View Railway on Coney Island, and assigned it by lease to the Brooklyn Heights Railroad. It was soon fitted with [[overhead lines|trolley wire]] for electric operation. A March 1, 1907 agreement allowed the company to operate through service from 38th Street and New Utrecht Avenue to Coney Island. Starting around 1908, electric trains began operating as a branch of the [[BMT West End Line]] from [[Bath Junction]] to Coney Island, with trains coming from [[Park Row (BMT station)|Park Row]] in Manhattan via the [[Brooklyn Bridge]] and [[BMT Fifth Avenue Line]]. [[Streetcar]]s ran over the rest of the line to Bay Ridge, from New Utrecht Avenue and 62nd Street to 65th Street and Third Avenue. In 1907, connecting tracks were built connecting to the West End Line just north of [[Coney Island Creek]] in order to bring Sea Beach trains into [[West End Terminal|West End Depot]]. The original alignment was retained for freight service only.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe portion of the line between 62nd Street and New Utrecht Avenue and Third Avenue and 65th Street was replaced by bus service between December 1, 1913 and June 23, 1914, when trolley service resumed service before being eliminated on June 22, 1915.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[File:Sea Beach Line.png|thumb|200px|Part of a 1915 brochure for the line|alt=]]\n\nAs part of the [[Dual Contracts]], and while the Fourth Avenue Subway Line was being constructed the BRT dug a four-track open cut and built high-level platforms for subway operation on the Sea Beach Line. Trolley cars started using the new open cut between Avenue T and 86th Street on January 9, 1914. Service was gradually extended until the new Sea Beach Line opened for full subway service. Two subway cars with poles were run between Third Avenue and New Utrecht Avenue and started operating on March 16, 1915. Additional cars were equipped with poles and operated service on the line from May 1, 1915 until the line opened for full subway service on June 22, 1915, with trains running between Coney Island and [[Chambers Street (BMT Nassau Street Line)|Chambers Street]] in [[Lower Manhattan]]. Service started with two- and three-car trains operating via the Fourth Avenue local track and the Manhattan Bridge south tracks. The express tracks were finished several weeks later. When the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] was extended south from the Sea Beach Line on January 15, 1916, the Sea Beach trains were shifted to the express tracks on Fourth Avenue, with Fourth Avenue trains providing local service.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe tracks over the north side of the [[Manhattan Bridge]] opened on September 4, 1917, along with part of the [[BMT Broadway Line]]. All Sea Beach service was moved to the new line, ending at [[14th Street\u2013Union Square (New York City Subway)|14th Street\u2013Union Square]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1917/09/05/archives/open-first-section-of-broadway-line-train-carrying-1000-passengers.html|title=OPEN FIRST SECTION OF BROADWAY LINE; Train Carrying 1,000 Passengers Runs from Fourteenth Street to Coney Island.REGULAR SERVICE BEGINSNew Road Is Expected to Relieve Old System of 15,000 PersonsDaily in Rush Hours. Service Commissioners Jubliant. Schedule Not Fully Arranged.|last=|first=|date=September 5, 1917|work=|access-date=November 5, 2016|issn=0362-4331|via=|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> This was extended to [[Times Square\u201342nd Street/Port Authority Bus Terminal (New York City Subway)|Times Square\u201342nd Street]] on January 5, 1918.\n\nIn 1924, the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation|BMT]] assigned numbers to its services. The ''Sea Beach Line'' service became the [[BMT 4|4]]. This has since become the {{NYCS service|N}} train. In general, Sea Beach service has always run express in Manhattan and on Fourth Avenue in Brooklyn, ending at 42nd Street and later [[57th Street \u2013 Seventh Avenue (BMT Broadway Line)|57th Street]]. The {{NYCS service|NX}} began on November 27, 1967 as a \"super-express\" from [[Brighton Beach (BMT Brighton Line)|Brighton Beach]] on the [[BMT Brighton Line]] through [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]], and along the Sea Beach Line express tracks to 57th Street with only seven stops between Stillwell Avenue and 57th Street, three in Brooklyn and four in Manhattan. This service was discontinued on April 15, 1968 due to low ridership, and no regular trains have used the Sea Beach express tracks since.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejoekorner.com/lines/suball-frame.htm|title=SUBWAY LINE NAMES|last=Korman|first=Joseph D.|date=|website=www.thejoekorner.com|publisher=|access-date=October 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"erictb.info2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.erictb.info/linehistory.html|title=NYCT Line by Line History|last=Bolden|first=Eric|date=|publisher=|access-date=October 30, 2016|work=erictb.info}}</ref><ref>[http://www.thejoekorner.com/scripted-ticket-display.shtm?http://www.thejoekorner.com/subway-sun/P008486.gif service notice], effective April 15, 1968</ref>\n\n===Later years===\n\nIn the 1970s, there was a proposal to renovate the Sea Beach open cut, which were deteriorating to the point that a retaining wall along the line was in danger of collapsing onto the tracks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/04/28/archives/subway-repairs-voted-by-city-east-river-duct-work.html|title=Subway Repairs Voted By City|last=Fowler|first=Glenn|date=1974-04-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Funding was allocated for the line's infrastructure improvements in 1975.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/10/19/archives/subway-improvements-set-by-mta.html|title=Subway Improvements Set by M.T.A.|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|date=1975-10-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> More than $20 million was earmarked for New York City Subway projects in 1977, including for upgrades to the Sea Beach line.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/10/04/archives/mta-receives-280-million-in-federal-grants.html|title=M.T.A. Receives $280 Million in Federal Grants|last=Burks|first=Edward C. Burks|date=1977-10-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-09-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n{{wikinews|New York City Subway N service to be restored to Coney Island May 29, via the Sea Beach Line}}\n\nWhen [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (New York City Subway)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]] was closed for reconstruction from 1993\u20131995 and November 4, 2001 to May 29, 2005, [[86th Street (BMT Sea Beach Line)|86th Street]] was the southern terminal for the N train.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/n_to_coneyisland.htm |title=Noteworthy - N restored to Coney Island |date=2005-05-07 |access-date=2016-09-18 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050507105016/http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/n_to_coneyisland.htm |archivedate=2005-05-07 }}</ref><ref name=\"erictb.info2\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/n_to_coneyisland.htm|title=Noteworthy - N restored to Coney Island|date=May 7, 2005|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=September 18, 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050507105016/http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/n_to_coneyisland.htm|archivedate=May 7, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, it was announced that the line would under extensive renovation. All stations would be waterproofed, with their [[station building|house]]s and passageways remodeled and stairways rebuilt; they would also get [[New York City Subway#Help Point|Help Points]], and turnstiles would be added to each station. In addition, [[graffiti]], which is prevalent on the line, would be mitigated; this required going onto private property to remove graffiti and fix the roofs of the stations. [[Eighth Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Eighth Avenue]] and [[New Utrecht Avenue/62nd Street (New York City Subway)|New Utrecht Avenue/62nd Street]] would get wheelchair-accessible [[elevator]]<nowiki/>s. The {{US$|395700000|link=yes}} project was scheduled to begin in the winter of 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homereporternews.com/news/general/two-elevators-coming-to-the-n-line-during-massive-rehabilitation/article_f6bc6a20-2d28-11e3-a283-001a4bcf887a.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313022820/http://www.homereporternews.com/news/general/two-elevators-coming-to-the-n-line-during-massive-rehabilitation/article_f6bc6a20-2d28-11e3-a283-001a4bcf887a.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 13, 2014 |title=Two elevators coming to the N line during massive rehabilitation |date=October 4, 2013 |accessdate=May 24, 2014 }}</ref> but work began in late June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bensonhurstbean.com/2012/07/hazards-of-the-sea-beach-n-line-stations/|title=Hazards Of The Sea Beach N Line Stations|author=lvladimirova|work=Bensonhurst Bean}}</ref>\n\nFunding for the renovation was provided for in the 2010\u20132014 Capital Program.<ref>http://web.mta.info/capital/pdf/CapitalConstruction_1014.pdf</ref> From January 18, 2016 to May 22, 2017, the Manhattan-bound platforms of all stations were closed. At Bay Parkway and Eighth Avenue, temporary wooden platforms were placed on the southbound express trackbed.<ref name=\"mta.info N Line Sea Beach 2016\">{{Cite web|title = N Line Sea Beach - 2016|url = http://web.mta.info/nyct/service/NLine2016/|website = web.mta.info|access-date = 2016-01-18}}\n\n*{{cite web | title=9 Brooklyn N train stations to shut down for 14 months | website=am New York | date=2016-01-14 | url=http://www.amny.com/transit/n-train-closings-9-brooklyn-station-platforms-to-close-for-14-months-1.11325586 | accessdate=2016-01-18 }}\n*{{cite web | last=Katinas | first=Paula | title=Commuter headache: MTA to renovate N train stations | website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle | date=2014-12-18 | url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/12/18/commuter-headache-mta-renovate-n-train-stations | accessdate=2016-01-18 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027143028/http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/12/18/commuter-headache-mta-renovate-n-train-stations | archive-date=2018-10-27 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/maps/subway_map.pdf |title=New York City Subway Map |date=May 1, 2017 |website=mta.info |publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502011736/http://web.mta.info/nyct/maps/subway_map.pdf |archive-date=May 2, 2017 |url-status=dead |access-date=May 2, 2017 }}</ref> After a two-month halt in construction, the Coney Island bound platforms closed on July 31, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brooklynreporter.com/story/manhattan-bound-service-return-n-stations-sea-beach-line/|title=Manhattan-bound service to return to N stations on Sea Beach Line|last=DeJesus|first=Jaime|date=May 17, 2017|website=brooklynreporter.com|language=|access-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/manhattan-bound-service-returns-n-stations-sea-beach-line|title=Manhattan-Bound Service Returns to N Stations on Sea Beach Line|last=|first=|date=May 17, 2017|website=www.mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref> The southbound platforms at Kings Highway, Avenue U, and 86th Street reopened on October 29, 2018, with closures lasting a month less than for their northbound counterparts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/181113_1030_Transit.pdf|title=Transit & Bus Committee Meeting - November 2018|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2018|website=mta.info|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|pages=164|access-date=November 10, 2018}}</ref> The southbound platforms between Eighth Avenue and Bay Parkway, however, were closed until July 1, 2019, six months longer than their northern counterparts and seven months longer than the other three southbound platforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://travel.mtanyct.info/serviceadvisory/routeStatusResult.aspx?tag=ALL&date=07/01/2019&time=&method=getstatus4|title=Planned Service Changes for: Monday, July 1, 2019|date=July 1, 2019|website=travel.mtanyct.info|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701152409/http://travel.mtanyct.info/serviceadvisory/routeStatusResult.aspx?tag=ALL&date=7%2F1%2F2019&time=&method=getstatus4|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> The elevators at New Utrecht Avenue/62nd Street opened on July 19, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/mta-installs-four-elevators-other-ada-features-new-utrecht-av62-st-station|title=MTA Installs Four Elevators, Other ADA Features at New Utrecht Av/62 St Station Complex|date=July 19, 2019|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref> The northbound elevator at Eighth Avenue opened on November 4, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/mta-opens-new-elevator-8-av-northbound-access-improve-accessibility|title=MTA Opens New Elevator at 8 Av for Northbound Access to Improve Accessibility in Southern Brooklyn|date=November 4, 2019|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=November 4, 2019}}</ref> From October 21, 2019 until April 27, 2020, N trains {{show by date|2020|04|27|will terminate|terminated}} at 86th Street so work could be completed to protect Coney Island Yard from flooding. An out-of-system transfer was made available between the N at 86th Street and the F at [[Avenue X station]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://new.mta.info/system_modernization/coneyislandyard|title=Preparing for Climate Change: Protecting the Coney Island Yard|last=|first=|date=September 16, 2019|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Chaining information ==\n\nThe Sea Beach Line is [[New York City Subway chaining|chained]] '''BMT E'''.<ref name=\"tracks\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thejoekorner.com/out-the-front/index-chaining.shtm|title = New York City Subway Chaining|date = |accessdate = May 24, 2014|website = The JoeKorNer|publisher = |last = Korman|first = Joe}}</ref>\n\n==Station listing==\n\n{{NYCS service legend|alltimes=show|rushonly=show}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Neighborhood\n!{{Access icon}}\n!Station\n!Tracks\n!Services\n!Opened\n!Transfers and notes\n|-\n!colspan=7 style=\"background-color: silver;\"|splits from the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS Sea Beach|time=show}})\n|-\n!colspan=7 style=\"background-color: silver;\"|Two center express tracks begin ({{NYCS Sea Beach express|time=show}})<br />(Southbound track disconnected from line; northbound track bi-directional)\n|-\n|[[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]]\n| align=center | {{Access icon}}&nbsp;\u2191\n|[[Eighth Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Eighth Avenue]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show}}\n|June 22, 1915\n| Station is [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA-accessible]] in the northbound direction only.\n|-\n|[[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]]\n|\n|[[Fort Hamilton Parkway (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Fort Hamilton Parkway]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show}}\n|June 22, 1915\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Bensonhurst, Brooklyn|Bensonhurst]]\n| align=center | {{Access icon}}\n|[[New Utrecht Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|New Utrecht Avenue]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show}}\n|June 22, 1915\n|[[BMT West End Line]] ({{NYCS West End north|time=show}}) at [[62nd Street (BMT West End Line)|62nd Street]]\n|-\n|\n|[[18th Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|18th Avenue]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show}}\n|June 22, 1915\n|\n|-\n|\n|[[20th Avenue (BMT Sea Beach Line)|20th Avenue]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show}}\n|June 22, 1915\n|\n|-\n|\n|[[Bay Parkway (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Bay Parkway]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show}}\n|June 22, 1915\n|\n|-\n!colspan=7 style=\"background-color: silver;\"|Southbound express track reconnects to line ({{NYCS Sea Beach express|time=show}})\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Gravesend, Brooklyn|Gravesend]]\n|\n|[[Kings Highway (BMT Sea Beach Line)|Kings Highway]]\n|local\n|{{NYCS Sea Beach local|time=show